        Conclusions
        In this study, we cloned the <ENAMEX TYPE="ANIMAL">full-length mouse</ENAMEX> and human
        
        COP1 <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">cDNAs</ENAMEX>. Furthermore, we
        demonstrated that mammalian <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT">COP1</ENAMEX> is associated with
        ubiquitinated <ENAMEX TYPE="SUBSTANCE">proteins</ENAMEX> in vivo and itself a substrate of
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">ubiquitination</ENAMEX>. Finally, through subcellular localization
        studies, we identified a unique type of nuclear import
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">signal</ENAMEX> and a classic nuclear export signal within the
        <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">N</ENAMEX>-terminal region of mammalian <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">COP1</TIMEX>, which might be
        important for regulation of the mammalian COP1
        activity.
      
      
